          "body": "Chapter 4 ends with golden doors (4:22) but does not end the story. The furnishings are complete — 'Solomon made all these things' (4:19) — but the house is still empty of its most important occupant. The Chronicler withholds the climax deliberately. The ark has not yet been brought in; the glory has not yet descended. Chapter 5 will supply what chapter 4 cannot: 'the glory of the LORD filled the house of God' (5:14). Chapter 4 is the preparation; chapter 5 is the presence. The theological implication is one the Chronicler wants his post-exilic audience to feel: the most meticulously furnished house in Israel's history could not contain God by virtue of its furnishings. God fills it by His own sovereign will and glory. The perfect temple is necessary but not sufficient. The presence of God is always grace."
