        "excerpt": "He also made ten basins in which to wash… but the sea was for the priests to wash in.",
        "body": "The chapter's longest single description is given to the molten sea (4:2-5), and verse 6 provides the chapter's single most explicit functional distinction: the basins cleanse the burnt-offering materials; the sea cleanses the priests themselves. Two water systems, one temple — the Chronicler is showing that purification is not a uniform act but a graduated one, calibrated to the purity required for each approach to God.\n\nThe molten sea's dimensions (ten cubits diameter, five cubits high, 3,000 baths capacity) have long attracted interpretive attention. The twelve oxen beneath it, facing all four compass directions in groups of three (4:4), are the most symbolically dense feature of the chapter. The most contextually defensible reading is that twelve corresponds to the twelve tribes — the sea rests on Israel's totality, facing every direction of the world. A minority reading, advocated by some ancient Near Eastern scholars, finds a cosmological parallel with Mesopotamian creation imagery where the sea (*yam*) represents primordial waters held under divine control. Both readings may be present; the Chronicler is writing in a theological idiom where cosmological and covenantal imagery overlap without contradiction.\n\nThe functional distinction of verse 6 should not be passed over lightly. The burnt-offering basins serve the sacrificial system — they wash what is about to be burned. But the priests who perform that washing themselves require purification of a different order. They are not objects being cleansed for burning; they are persons drawing near to God. The sea's size — vast enough to hold 3,000 baths — suggests that the provision for priestly purification is inexhaustible. There is always enough water. There is never a moment when the priest must approach God without the means to be clean.\n\nThe New Testament application is careful here. The molten sea has been widely interpreted as a type of Christian baptism (so many patristic commentators), but a more contextually precise reading sees it as the provision for the ongoing purification of those already consecrated to priestly service — which maps precisely to the Christian's ongoing cleansing through confession and the intercession of Christ (1 John 1:9; Hebrews 7:25). We do not re-enter the bronze altar (justification is once for all); we return to the sea (the purification of the justified is continuous).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yam* (sea) — the same word for the Mediterranean, for the Red Sea, and for the primordial deep of Genesis 1:2. Its use for this basin is theologically charged. *Rachats* (wash) appears twice in v.6 — once for the basins, once for the sea — underscoring that the same verb serves two distinct functions. *Olah* (burnt offering) — literally 'what goes up,' the wholly-consumed offering signaling total surrender."
