        "body": "Three verses describe the placement of ten golden lampstands (4:7), ten tables (4:8), and the two courts (4:9). The lampstands and tables are both multiplications of the single Mosaic originals — one menorah and one showbread table in the tabernacle becoming ten of each in the temple. The Chronicler is careful to note that the lampstands are made 'in the way prescribed for them' (*mishpat*, 4:7): Solomon's innovation is quantitative, not qualitative. The prescribed pattern is honored; the scale is expanded.\n\nThe significance of the lampstands inside the nave (hekhal) is that they provide the only light in a windowless interior. Without the lampstands burning continually before the inner sanctuary (devir, 4:20), the nave would be in total darkness. This is not incidental. The God who IS light (1 John 1:5) — whose presence will fill this house in chapter 5 — dwells in a space that human craft keeps illuminated with pure gold lamps. The lampstands do not generate the divine light; they maintain the space in readiness for it. The church's proclamation of the Word is the New Testament analogy: Revelation 1:20 identifies the seven lampstands as the seven churches — not the sources of Christ's light, but the maintained vessels in which His light is held before the world.\n\nThe hundred golden bowls (4:8) and the two courts (4:9) complete the outer-to-inner movement of this section. The great court admits Israel's worshiping assembly; the priests' court is reserved for those in consecrated service. The bronze doors of both courts (4:9) mark the thresholds. Even the gates of the courts are constructed to specification, overlaid with the material appropriate to their location: bronze, not gold, because the courts are not yet the innermost presence.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mishpat* (prescribed manner, v.7; v.20) — the same word used for legal ordinance and divine judgment; here it means 'according to the prescribed specification,' grounding the lampstands' design in divine command, not Solomonic aesthetics. *Hekhal* (temple/nave) refers to the main hall of the sanctuary, distinct from the *devir* (inner sanctuary/most holy place)."
