        "body": "Verses 11-17 represent the chapter's most inventory-dense section — a retrospective summary of everything Huram made, running through the pillars, the capitals, the networks, the pomegranates, the stands, and the sea once more. The Chronicler here follows his Kings source closely (cf. 1 Kings 7:40-47) while maintaining the theological emphasis that all of this was 'for the house of God' (4:11) and 'for the house of the LORD' (4:16).\n\nThe pomegranates deserve mention. Four hundred pomegranates adorn the two networks covering the pillar capitals (4:13) — two rows of two hundred each. The pomegranate (*rimmon*) in Old Testament symbolism is associated with fertility, abundance, and the goodness of the promised land (Numbers 13:23; Deuteronomy 8:8; Song of Solomon 4:3). Placed at the tops of the entrance pillars (Jachin and Boaz from ch.3), they frame the entry to Yahweh's house with the imagery of overflowing blessing — the God who dwells here is the God of the land's bounty, not a deity of scarcity.\n\nThe casting site (Jordan plain between Succoth and Zeredah, 4:17) grounds the project in historical geography while also hinting at its industrial scale. You do not cast the molten sea in Jerusalem; you cast it in the clay-rich valley, transport it, and install it. The logistics imply months or years of preparation work before a single furnishing is placed. The temple's glory is not spontaneous; it is the product of sustained, skillful, obedient labor in service of a divine design.\n\nThe concluding summary — 'the weight of the bronze could not be found out' (4:18) — is the Chronicler's shorthand for immeasurable provision. It echoes the language of divine generosity throughout Chronicles (2 Chronicles 1:15, Solomon's silver and gold 'as plentiful as stone'). God's house is not furnished with what could be weighed and calculated; it overflows human accounting.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kalah* (finished, v.11) — the same verb that closes Genesis 2:1-2 (God 'finished' His work) and Exodus 40:33 (Moses 'finished' the tabernacle). The Chronicler places Huram's completion in that tradition. *Rimmon* (pomegranate) — a fertility symbol in both Israelite and ancient Near Eastern iconography; their placement at the pillar tops frames the entrance to the temple with blessing-imagery."
